# Backend C# — Critical Rules Summary

Full convention guides are in `docs/conventions/backend/`. Read the relevant file before editing a layer. This file is a quick reference only.

## Twelve Critical Rules

### 1. Sealed by Default

All concrete classes and records MUST be `sealed` unless the type is explicitly a base class. Unsealed concrete types invite unintended inheritance and complicate future refactoring. See `docs/conventions/backend/02-domain-layer.md`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class CreatePostCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreatePostCommand, PostId> { }

// BAD:
class CreatePostCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreatePostCommand, PostId> { }
```

### 2. No Controllers - IEndpoint Only

All HTTP endpoints MUST implement `IEndpoint`. Inheriting from `ControllerBase` or `Controller` is forbidden. Violating this rule bypasses the IEndpoint discovery mechanism and introduces MVC conventions that are not supported by these standards. See `docs/conventions/backend/05-api-layer.md`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class CreatePostEndpoint : IEndpoint
{
    public void MapEndpoint(IEndpointRouteBuilder app) { ... }
}

// BAD:
[ApiController]
[Route("api/posts")]
class PostsController : ControllerBase { }
```

### 3. No Aggregate Loading in Query Handlers

Query handlers MUST inject `IXxxReadStore`, not `IXxxRepository`. Loading a full aggregate in a query handler couples read performance to write complexity and risks accidental state mutation. See `docs/conventions/backend/07-query-read-strategy.md`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class GetPostByIdQueryHandler : IQueryHandler<GetPostByIdQuery, PostResult>
{
    public GetPostByIdQueryHandler(IPostReadStore postReadStore) { ... }
}

// BAD:
sealed class GetPostByIdQueryHandler : IQueryHandler<GetPostByIdQuery, PostResult>
{
    public GetPostByIdQueryHandler(IPostRepository postRepository) { ... }
}
```

### 4. Correct Exception Hierarchy

Validators throw `ApplicationValidationException` subclasses (HTTP 400). Repositories throw `AggregateNotFoundException` subclasses (HTTP 404). Aggregates throw `DomainException` subclasses (HTTP 409). Using the wrong type produces incorrect HTTP responses. See `docs/conventions/backend/06-exception-hierarchy.md`.

### 5. CancellationToken Named Exactly

The last parameter of every async method MUST be named exactly `cancellationToken`. Using `ct`, `token`, or `cancel` reduces searchability and violates the naming convention. See `docs/conventions/shared/naming.md`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
Task<PostResult> HandleAsync(GetPostByIdQuery query, CancellationToken cancellationToken);

// BAD:
Task<PostResult> HandleAsync(GetPostByIdQuery query, CancellationToken ct);
```

### 6. No Handlers or Validators in Contracts Projects

`Application.Write.Contracts` and `Application.Read.Contracts` contain only records and interfaces. Placing handlers or validators there pollutes the public contract surface and breaks the dependency direction. See `docs/conventions/backend/03-application-layer.md`.

### 7. No External Libraries in Application.Reactions

Event handlers MUST define narrow interfaces for external capabilities. Infrastructure implements those interfaces. Adding EF Core, email clients, or HTTP clients directly to `Application.Reactions` violates the dependency rule and makes event handlers untestable without real infrastructure. See `docs/conventions/backend/03-application-layer.md`.

### 8. WebApi References Contracts Only

`WebApi` endpoint code MUST reference only `Application.Write.Contracts` and `Application.Read.Contracts`. Referencing the implementation projects from endpoint code exposes handler internals to the API layer and defeats the purpose of the Contracts boundary. See `docs/conventions/backend/05-api-layer.md`.

### 9. Explicit Constructors for DI

Handler, validator, and endpoint classes MUST use explicit constructors for dependency injection. Primary constructors are not permitted in DI scenarios because they reduce the legibility of injection points. See `docs/conventions/backend/03-application-layer.md`.

### 10. AwesomeAssertions in All Tests

All test assertions MUST use AwesomeAssertions. Using xUnit `Assert.*` directly violates the assertion library convention and produces less readable failure messages. See `docs/conventions/backend/08-testing.md`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
post.State.Should().BeOfType<PublishedPostState>();

// BAD:
Assert.IsType<PublishedPostState>(post.State);
```

### 11. Guid.CreateVersion7() for New IDs

All new aggregate ID generation MUST use `Guid.CreateVersion7()`. Using `Guid.NewGuid()` produces random GUIDs that fragment database clustered indexes. See `docs/conventions/backend/02-domain-layer.md`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
public static PostId New() => new(Guid.CreateVersion7());

// BAD:
public static PostId New() => new(Guid.NewGuid());
```

### 12. Mermaid for All Diagrams

All diagrams in documentation files MUST use Mermaid syntax in a fenced code block. ASCII art diagrams are forbidden because they cannot be updated programmatically and degrade readably.
